In 2008 I made a quilt as a fundraiser for president @barackobama’s campaign. Inspired by Jessie Telfair’s 1975 Freedom quilt (in the collection of  the @nmaahc), the Yes We Can quilt raised close to $18k!! A few years later the @msumuseum commissioned one for their collection. 🙏🏻❤️

This king-size rendition of Yes We Can looks a crazy gameshow board at this stage, but I needed to get the blocks up to finalize colors for the remaining letters. 

Putting the first couple rows of blocks up was hard as it felt like the range of colors wasn’t working. 🫣 But as I tell my students — you can’t judge a thing when there isn’t enough of it to judge, and once all the completed letters were up I felt okay 😅  The letters are hand-appliqué, and I plan on finishing them up over my holiday break! 👏🏻👏🏻

Managed to get some rows sewn on this king size Yes We Can commission (thanks to @imholly52 and her expert block trimming). 

I spent most of the day correcting another quilt I finished sewing yesterday. I cut that quilt on the Friday before I tested positive — pushing through though I didn’t feel quite right because that’s what I always do. After all, there is always so much to be done, and never enough hours in the day (and the reality of being a solo-preneur is if you don’t get it out the door, you don’t get paid). 

Once it was together however, it was apparent that things were off. Luckily I was able to take it apart and correct the cutting, and it’s now back together and all good. A relatively painless reminder that my tendency to keep going no matter what is not only not healthy, but it’s ultimately not efficient, either. 

Tomorrow I will be resting and doing some quiet work at home. This quilt, and all the other things, will get done, eventually. ❤️

I’m honored to be included in @thomasknauer’s latest book, Quilting Out Loud. 

Thomas is is smart, thorough, and his book asks that we think about how letters, numbers, words and sentences change when used in a quilt, rather than on a screen or piece of paper. I made my first ‘talking quilt’ 20 years ago, influenced by the art of Barbara Kruger and historic quilts. Having studied graphic design in art school, working with text seemed like a natural way to combine my interests and experience.

Thomas has created an inspiring and thought-provoking body of text-based work that is featured in this book, AND includes all the practical info you need to incorporate his techniques in your own quilts. 

The book also features highlights of a handful of artists whose work I admire and am happy to be in company with, including @entropyalwayswins @alexisdeise @cauchycomplete @heidi.parkes and @molli_sparkles. 

To celebrate the launch of this powerful, inspiration-packed book, Thomas and  @ctpublishing are giving away a free digital copy for of the book to one of my followers! Tag a friend in the comments below who you think would appreciate this book. Can’t wait to see what you have to ‘say’. ❤️ I’ll pick a winner midnight EST Friday Feb 10.
